<head>
<title>CSS Template</title>
<style>
* {
  box-sizing: border-box;
}
header {
  background-color: #e83140;
  color: white;
  padding: 10px;
  text-align: center;
  font-size: 35px;
  color: white;
}
nav {
  float: left;
  width: 20%;
  background: #f5dcc4;
  padding: 20px;
  height: 300px;
}
article {
  float: left;
  padding: 20px;
  width: 50%;
  height: 100px;
}
.articleLight {
  background-color: #f5f5bc;
}
.articleDark {
  background-color: #f5f590;
}
aside {
  float: right;
  padding: 20px;
  width: 30%;
  height: 300px;
}
.asideLight {
  background-color: #d6f2b3;
}
.asideDark {
  background-color: #c7f095;
}
section:after {
  content: ";
  display: table;
  clear: both;
}
footer {
  background-color: #71498a;
  color: white;
  padding: 10px;
  text-align: center;
  color: white;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<h2>Structural Tags Exercise</h2>
<p>Here below are exemplified the structural tags.</p>
<header>
  <h2>The Header</h2>
</header>
<section>
  <nav>
    <h4>The Navigation (nav)</h4>
    <p>For nav CSS use a float to the left, padding of 20 pixels, a height of 300 pixels, and 20% of the page width.</p>
  </nav>
  <aside class="asideDark">
    <h1>This is the aside</h1>
    <p>For aside CSS use a float to the right, padding of 20 pixels, a height of 300 pixels, and 30% of the page width.</p>
  </aside>
  <article class="articleLight">
    <h1>This is an Article</h1>
    <p>For the article CSS use a float to the left, padding of 20 pixels, a height of 100 pixels, and 40% of the page width.</p>
  </article>
  <article class="articleDark">
    <h1>This is another Article</h1>
    <p>Note that the nav, both articles, and both asides are in the same section.</p>
  </article>
  <article class="articleLight">
    <h1>This is the third Article</h1>
    <p>Can you create it?.</p>
  </article>
</section>
<footer>
  <p>The Footer</p>
</footer>
</body>
